text:
(1)
Fort Washington Ave., at the N.W. corner of West 165th Street, showing across rocks at that point, units of Cornell University-Presbyterian Hospital Center.

P. L. Sperr. June 15, 1937.

(2)
A similar view at an earlier date, as photographed in a northwestward direction from West 165th Street (foreground), slightly east of Fort Washington Ave. (center). Note at the right, several of the buildings that were replaced by the Neurological Institute as seen in No. 1. The prominent building appearing in both views is the Presbyterian Hospital School of Nursing.

P. L. Sperr. November 9, 1927.

text:
(1)
Excavating in rock, Fort Washington Avenue at N. E. corner of 165th Street.
P.L. Sperr, Photographer. September 29, 1931.

(2)
The same, at a later date, showing The Eye Institute (a unit of Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Centre) which was erected on the site seen in view No. 1. It bears No. 635 West 165th Street. This view is westward on West 165th Street from a point east of Fort Washington Ave.
June 15, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

title: Manhattan: Fort Washington Aven - 165th Street

text:
Fort Washington Ave., west side, south from West 165th Street, showing the rear of the grounds of the New York Institution for the Deaf. On the right appears the Vocational School. No. 2 of this set is from a vantage point at 164th Street and shows another unit, this being at the N.W. corner of 163rd Street.

June 15, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

text:
Fort Washington Ave., north from West 165th Street and showing prominently on the west side of same two units of Columbia University-Presbyterian Medical Center; the Presbyterian Hospital School of Nursing and the Neurological Institute. The latter is the center structure.

June 15, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
